Section1.Para:
The minor alloying method has been considered as an effective technique for improving the plasticity and/or ductility of bulk metallic glasses [1, 2]. Concerning monolithic bulk metallic glasses, generalized with the minor alloying method, Xia et al. have reported ternary bulk metallic glasses by using minor alloying of the Cu8Zr5 icosahedron [3]. To be specific, they used the deepest eutectic composition of the Cu–Zr binary phase diagram, Cu61.8Zr38.2, as the original composition point, which was alloyed with Nb, Sn, Mo, Ag, and Ta elements, respectively, and consequently a series of Cu-based bulk metallic glasses were development. Addition of Be element into Cu–Zr binary eutectic compositions also indicate the improvement of the glass-forming ability. Importantly, Cu47.5Zr40Be12.5 bulk metallic glass exhibits apparent double glass transitions (T

                  g
                ) and enhanced plasticity as well as improved GFA [4]. In a previous paper, the In element used as an alloying element added into Cu–Zr–Ti ternary bulk metallic glasses led to results indicating a very excellently positive effect on the glass-forming ability [5].

We have investigated the Cu52Zr37Ti8In3 bulk metallic glass by nanoindentation in three different ways. Load-control nanoindentation was used to investigate the effect of the loading rate on the hardness and Young’s modulus. Young’s modulus of the specimen shows a loading rate dependence, but the hardness does not. A generalized Kelvin model was employed to analyze the indentation creep data. The compliance spectrum and retardation spectrum were derived. The results showed that the magnitude of glassy compliance (J

                  g
                ) in the present work is equal to 10−10 Pa−1 and the creep process at a holding load of 70 mN has higher relaxation than others. Furthermore, storage compliance and loss compliance were also discussed. It can be found that the magnitude of the loss compliance is far lower than that of the storage compliance. Consequently, Cu52Zr37Ti8In3 bulk metallic glass has a very excellent elastic-deformation capacity at room temperature. For characterizing the change of the hardness and Young’s modulus referring to indentation depth, a depth-control nanoindentation analysis was conducted. We found that both the hardness and Young’s modulus decrease with nanoindentation depth.
